# Shared Derivation — Lift Don't Duplicate

When you derive a UI rule from fields on a **shared type** (e.g., `ImageView`, `JobRow`, `MatchView`), the derivation must live in the **shared component** that renders that type, not in each consumer.

## Concrete heuristic

If a derivation reads a field that is shared across surfaces — e.g., `image.stack_id`, `image.is_stack_representative`, `image.stack_member_count` — and produces a piece of UI (badge, overlay, accent), put the rendering in the shared component and let consumers opt out via props if they truly need to.

## Pattern (correct)

```5:35:apps/visualizer/frontend/src/components/image-view/ImageTile.tsx
function deriveStackOverlay(image: ImageView): ReactNode | null {
  const count = image.stack_member_count ?? 0;
  if (!image.is_stack_representative || count <= 1) return null;
  return <Badge variant="muted">{formatStackCountBadge(count)}</Badge>;
}
```

Consumers (CatalogTab, BestPhotosGrid, UnpostedCatalogPanel) just render `<ImageTile image={…} />` — no per-grid derivation, no wrapper components.

## Anti-pattern (caught the hard way in phase 7.1)

```tsx
// CatalogImageWithStack.tsx
const showBadge = image.is_stack_representative && (image.stack_member_count ?? 0) > 1;

// BestPhotoTileWithStack.tsx — DUPLICATE
const isRep = image.is_stack_representative;
const count = image.stack_member_count ?? 0;
const showStackBadge = isRep && count > 1;
```

Two consumers, identical derivation, two places to update when the rule changes (or to forget to update — which is what happened).

## Workflow

When you find yourself writing such a derivation in a consumer:

1. **Stop.** Open the shared renderer for the type (e.g., `ImageTile.tsx`).
2. Check if the derivation belongs there. If yes, lift it.
3. Run the callsite sweep (see `dry-callsite-sweep.mdc`) to find any other consumer doing the same thing — delete the duplication.
4. Update tests on the shared component to cover the new derivation; consumer tests should only assert delegation, not re-test the derivation.

## Caller-supplied overlays

Consumers can still add badges via `overlayBadges` props. The shared component must merge caller overlays with auto-derived ones; never overwrite.

## Why this exists

The DRY violation in phase 7.1 cost a full session of fix work. The shared `ImageTile` was the obvious home for stack-rep badge logic but two wrappers had quietly grown around it.
